ÅCHAPTER1

THEMIDDLEENGLISHHUNTINGMANUALSÄ


TheMiddleEnglishhuntingmanualsformedpartofasubstantial
bodyofhuntingliteratureinseveralEuropeanvernaculars.
AlthoughrelatedtotheirEuropeancounterparts,theMiddle
Englishtextsdevelopedinadifferentdirection.Theyemphasise
differentaspectsofhuntingactivity,andreflectdifferent
socialattitudestowardsthehunt.Ingeneral,theContinental
huntingtextsaremarkedbyagreateremphasisonutilitarian
detailthanwefindintheMiddleEnglishmanuals.Theydonot
shirkfromrepresentingproceduresfortrapping,snaringand
poisoninganimals-allofwhichtheEnglishwritersshunas
ignobleactivitiesnotworthyofthehunter.TheEnglishmanuals
concentrateonthenoblehuntfor'beastsofvenery'-thehart,
hareandboar-andgenerallyonthehuntÑparforceÄ:onhorseback
usinghounds.TheContinentalmanualsgiveagooddealofuseful
practicalinstruction,buttheEnglishtextsfocusonthe
peripheral,socialdetailsoflanguage,ritualprocedure,horn
musicandhuntingcries.TheFrenchmanualscouldteachamanhow
tohunt;theEnglishmanualstaughthuntsmenhowtoappear
gentlemen.


