ÑTheBokeofHuntyngÄ,betterknownasthesecondtreatiseinthe
ÑBokeofStAlbansÄ,waswrittenearlyinthefifteenthcentury.ê08,7Ä
TheÑBokeÄiswide-ranginginitssubjectmatter,including
informationonthecategorisationofanimals,terminology,hunts
forthehart,hare,boar,roedeerandbuck,'breaking'(cutting
up)thecarcassofthedeerandboar,andvariousother
miscellaneousitems.Mostofthetextispresentedintheformof
aversemonologuebya'dame'instructingherchildren,butsome
materialisgivenasadialoguebetweena'master'andhis'man'.
Itispoorlyarranged,andhasnologicalstructure:consecutive
subjectsareoftenunrelatedandsomematerialisrepeated.The
materialappearsinadifferentorderintheBokeofStAlbans
andeachofthetwomanuscriptversions.

Itwasnotuncommoninthefourteenthandfifteenthcenturiesfor
suchfactualworkstoappearinverse.ê05,8ÄAlthoughtheversemay
havehadslightmnemonicvalue,themetreisoftenunevenand
sometimesdifficult,andtherhymewordsarefrequentlytagsor
incidentalphraseswhichwouldhavebeenoflittleuseasanÑaide
memoireÄ.Itseemslikelythattheverseformwasintendedtolend
thetexttheairofauthorityandformality,orperhapssimply
makethematerialmorepalatable.Other'literary'featuresare
thefictitious'characters'ofdameandchild,masterandman,
andthereferencetotheauthorityofTristanintheopening
lines:

Wheresoeveryefarebyfrythorbyfell,
MyderechyldetakehedehowTristramdoothyoutell(lines1-2)

