E
ÄTheÑBokeofHuntyngÄisthemostpuzzlingandperhapstheleast
satisfactoryoftheMiddleEnglishhuntingmanuals.Thetwo
narrativeframeworksofthemaster/mandialogueandthedame's
monologueareintegratedonlyinthemostrudimentaryfashionby
theconsistentverseform.Thejumbledorderofthematerial
furtherunderminesthetext'spretensions.The'literary'
featuresmighthaveenhancedtheworkifithadbeencompetently
executedonthemostbasiclevel,buttheyareinsufficient-and
inthecaseofthemixeddramaticsituations,counterproductive-
asunifyingprinciplesthemselves.

ThelastMiddleEnglishmanual,theÑTretyseoffHuntyngÄ,ismore
difficulttodate.ê04,9ÄProbablywrittenduringthemid-orlate
fifteenthcentury,itgivesdetailsofthehuntsforthehare,
hart,buck,roedeerandfox,describesthebreakingofthedeer's
carcass,presentsmiscellaneousquestionsandanswers,and
describestheideal'shape'ofagreyhound.Theaccountsofthe
differenthuntsarepresentedinanarrative-likeform,giving
thehuntingcriesandhorncallstouseatvariousstagesand
followingthesequenceofthehuntfromkenneltokill.

TheÑTretyseÄisinmanywaysmoreorganisedthantheBokeandthe
ÑArtofVeneryÄ,thoughtherearefrequentlapsesinits
organisation.Theseriesofinstructionsforthevarioushunts
arecomparable,andmostsectionsareintroducedbyatitle.The
miscellaneousmatterislargelycollectedtogetherinthe
untitledseriesofquestionsratherthan,asintheothertwo
texts,scatteredthroughout.Asareferencework,itismore
usefulandcoherentthaneitheroftheothertwo,anditis
fairlyeasytofindinformationinit.

Thislasttextiswhollyindependentoftheothers,butthe
earliermanualsareinter-related.Therearetwoversionsofthe
ÑArtofVeneryÄ,thelaterversioncontainingalongaccountonthe
hare-huntwhichalsoappearsintheÑMasterofGameÄandtheÑBoke
ofHuntyngÄ.Itisnotpossibletotellwhichtexthastheprior
claimonthematerial.Theprocessofborrowingandcopying
betweentextsextendedtore-issuingtextsasnewworks.TheÑArt
ofVeneryÄwasadaptedandappearedinthefifteenthcenturyas
theÑCraftofVeneryÄ.ê03,10ÄTheÑBokeofHuntyngÄwasusedinthe
ÑBokeofStAlbansÄ,andthiswasinturnreissuedunderdifferent
titleswithonlysuperficialalterationsthreetimesinthe
N009:001801090004
ÄÑTheTretyseoffHuntyngÄ,editedbyAnneRooney,Scripta:
MedievalandRenaissancetextsandstudies,no.19(Brussels,
