ˇÄsixteenthandearlyseventeenthcenturies.ê07,11Ä

Thecontentsofthemanualsisoftensurprising.Inmanyareas
wherewemightexpectanextendedtreatment,theylackclear,
detailedandusefulinstructions,andthebalanceofmaterialis
rarelyinfavourofthepracticallyuseful.EventheÑMasterof
GameÄ,followingthelucidandpreciseÑLivredechasseÄ,omitssome
oftheFrenchdetailsofthehunt'sprocedureandreplacesthem
withanarrativeaccountofatypecharacteristicoftheEnglish
treatises.AlthoughGastonPhoebushadbeencarefultoexplain
almosteverypointofprocedureindetail,theDukeofYorkgives
adequate,butrarelyprolonged,explanations,andtheother
MiddleEnglishtreatisesgivelittleornone.Indeed,theother
treatisesappearnowtobevirtuallyuselessaspracticaltexts,
givingnoneofthedetailswewouldexpect:whichhoundsareused
ineachchase?aretheyallreleasedatonce?whichweapons
shouldthehuntercarry?howshouldhedress?inwhattypeof
terraincanheexpecttofindeachkindofanimal?TheÑMasterof
GameÄanswerssomeofthesequestionsbuttheothermanualsare
largelysilentonsuchmatters.Insteadtheyconcentrateonmore
esotericandlesspracticalconsiderations.Theproper
terminologyapplicabletovariousstagesofthehunt,andto
describingtheanimalanditsactivities,isgiven
disproportionateimportance.Similarly,theclassificationofthe
animalsplaysaprominentpartalthoughthevariouscriteriaby
whichtheyaregroupedhavenoapparentpracticalapplications.
Inpartsofallthemanuals,andthroughouttheÑTretyseoff
HuntynÄg,thesequencesofhornsignalsandhuntingcriestobe
usedisamajorpreoccupation.Thebodyofscatteredand
miscellaneousmanuscriptmaterialrelatingtothehuntis
likewiseconcernedwithterminology,classificationandhorn
calls.Allthisinformationis,strictlyspeaking,unnecessary.
Ithasnoplaceinhuntingwhenremovedfromtheparticular
cultureforwhichthemanualswerewritten.Thedetailswith
whichthemanualsconcernthemselvesarethefeaturesofthe
medievalchasewhichmadeitcourtlyandnon-utilitarian.But
thiswasnotthecasewiththeFrenchtextsonwhichtheEnglish
traditiondrew.


ÅFrenchpracticalityandEnglishsnobberyÄ

BecausetheÑMasterofGameÄistranslatedfromaFrenchwork,we
havearecordofhowtheEnglishwritersawhisownrequirements
differingfromthoseofaFrenchhuntsman.Aglanceatthe
N011:004201390007
ÄGervaseMarkham,ÑTheGentleman'sAcademie.OftheBokeofSt
Albans.ReducedintoaBetterMethodÄ(1595);William
Gryndall,ÑHawking,Hunting,FoulingandFishingÄ(1596),
facsimilebyTheEnglishExperience,no.463(Amsterdam,
