EnglishExperience,no.890(Amsterdam,1977).

E
ÄchangestheDukeofYorkmadewhenadaptinghissourcereveals
howheperceivedthedifferences.

ThetranslatedchaptersoftheÑMasterofGameÄusuallyfollowthe
sourcecloselyandaccuratelywiththeoccasionaladditionofan
explanatoryorqualifyingphrase.Wheretherearevariationsand
additions,theseservevariousfunctions.Someadditionsadvise
oncorrectEnglishterminology;othersanglicisethetext,
removingorexplainingreferencestoforeignpracticesand
changingreferencestodetailsofquotidianlifetoreflect
Englishcustoms.

ThealterationsandtheoriginalchaptersrevealhowEnglish
huntingpracticedifferedfromFrench,andshowwhatEnglish
hunterconsidereditthedutyofamanualtoteach,andwhichthe
Frenchneglected.Forexample,theEnglishwriteremphasises
thenobilityandspecialstatusofthehunt.Huntingasanoble
courtlyartrejectedmanyprocedureswhichmay,toanuninitiated
reader,seemtorepresentlegitimatehuntingpractices.TheDuke
ofYorkmakesclearthattheEnglishdistinguishbetweenhunting
andtrapping,consideringthelatterlessnobleandinappropriate
toagentleman:

Menslehareswi˛greyhoundesandwithrennynghoundesby
strengthe,asinEngelonde,butelliswhere˛eisleehem,Also
withsmalepocketesandwithpurs[n]etesandwithsmalenettis
wi˛harepipesandwithlongnettis...TrewelyItrowethatagood
hunteruoldslehemsofornogood.(p.14)(Italicisedtextis
notderivedfromLivredechasse.)

Heomitsthechaptersontrappinggame,alongwiththoseon
beastshedoesnotconsidersufficientlynoble.Heisalso
concernedwithpropriety;hedoesnotgivefullinstructionson
undoingthehart(cuttingupitscarcass),becausethisisa
skillnotappropriatetoahuntsman:

vndohym˛emoostwoodmanly...wondred#enot˛atysaywoodmanly
foritisapoynt˛atlonge˛toawoodmannyscraftand˛oughit
bewelsittyngtoanhunterfortocvndonit,neuer˛elatterit
longe˛moortowodemannyscraft˛antohunders.p.100

Themostinterestingofthepre-occupationsoftheEnglish
huntingmanuals,theconcernwithterminology,isparticularly
importantinmarkingthesocialdistinctiontheDukeofYork
pointstointhispassage.Thelanguageofthehunt,and
especiallythesocialstatusofthenoblehunter,willemergeas
importantfeaturesoftheliterarytreatmentsofthehuntwe
shalllookatlater.Itissignificant(thoughhardlysurprising)
thatthesameconcernsshouldappearinboththehuntingmanuals
andimaginativeliterature,andclearlyindicatesamajor
characteristicofthewayinwhichhuntingwasviewedbymedieval
Englishsociety.


Å'Markwellthesetermsfollowing'Ä

Thelanguageofthehuntperformedasociallydivisivefunction
andrenderedthehuntelitist,aclosedbooktotheuninitiated.
Allfourofthehuntingtreatisespayasmuchattentiontothe
correctnamesofthingsastotheirnature.SotheÑTretyseÄpauses
toexplainaterm:

ﬁen˛emaysterowethtosendafterhismen&hisueanters.so
shallhesayhym:'Goethwodethyowther#ewene˛atbestbe,
where˛ehertwyllcome',andassoneas˛eybewodedherryght
nameisclepyt'ueanters'.(lines133-6)


AndthroughouttheÑBokeofHuntyngÄ,thedameexhortsherpupilsto
usethecorrectnames,thoughherinsistenceisincorporatedinto
thetagsandisnotintrusive:

Mysonnys,whereyewalke,callyehemso.
Soyeshuldenaamesichdere,
AnddoasIyowlere.(lines62-4)

SomeoftheadditionstheDukeofYorkmadetothetextofÑLivre
dechasseÄintroduceEnglishterminology.Whilemanyaresimple
