Intheselines,manycategoriesareconstructedwhichfitonlya
singleanimal.Theauthorhasextendedthedivisionofthe
animalsbyallocatingspecialtermstoeachintoameansof
categorisation.Thisisincompletelyachieved,however:his
question'Howmany...?'demandsafigureforananswer,not
enumerationofthequalifyingbeasts.Theanswerinmostcases
mustbe'One',butthiswouldsurelyrevealtheinadequacyofhis
schemeofcategorisation.

Thatneithertheprincipaldivisionofanimalsintothe
categoriesofvenery,chaseandverminnorthesupplementary
divisionsaresusceptibletorationalexplanationservesfurther
tomarkthehuntasanareaofspecialknowledge.Theordinary
personcannotseeanylinkbetweenthehart,hare,boarandwolf,
oranyspecialdifferencebetweentheseanimalsandthefoxor
badger.Thecategorisationservesnopracticalpurpose,itdoes
notreflectsimilarhuntingtechniques,andservesonlytodivide
theelitewhoknowitfromthosewhodonot.'Noble'huntingis
restrictedtocorrectpursuitofthenoblebeasts:this
universally-acknowledgeddistinctionpermeatesliterarytextsin
whichaheromaybeimmediatelymarkedasnobleifheengagesin
ahartorboarhunt.Conversely,the'ignoble'beastswerenot
worthyofliteraryattention;withtheexceptionofdeer-drives,
therearehardlyanyhuntsotherthanforbeastsofveneryin
MiddleEnglishliterature,andnoexamplesofhuntsforvermin.


ÅConclusionÄ

Aswehaveseen,thehuntingmanualsarefarfromofferinglucid
instructionsinthepracticalaspectsofhunting.Instead,they
concentrateonthenon-utilitarian,courtlyaspectswhichweare
likelytoconsiderperipheraltotheactivity.

Asaworkingmanual,theÑTretyseÄagaindiffersfromtheother
huntingmanuals,whichmakeconspicuousdisplayoftheirnon-
utilitarianaspects.ThelargerpartoftheMasterofGameis
concernedwithbackgroundinformationwhich,thoughpractical,
wouldhardlyhavebeenconsultedinthefield,butratherreadat
leisure.TheÑBokeofHuntyngÄandtheÑArtofVeneryÄbothadoptthe
literarydevicesofdialogueormonologue,renderingthetexts
self-consciouslystylisedinawaywhichtheÑTretyseÄnever
attempts.NoteventheÑTretyseÄisutilitarianinthesenseof
providingdetailswhichmightcontributetothespeedycompletion
ofahuntforfood;itspreoccupation,likethatoftheother
manuals,iswiththeaspectsofthenoblehuntwhichmarkeditas
sportratherthananinnatelyusefulactivity.Butherethehorn
signalsandhuntingcries-andevensomeoftheterminology-
aregiveninthecontextofanaccountofthehunt'sprogress,
andthisformismaintainedconsistently.Itispossibleto
ÄimaginethehunterconsultingtheÑTretyseÄinthefieldfor
instructionsifhehadforgottenthehornsignalappropriateto
somecircumstance,whereasthiscouldhardlybethecasewithany
oftheothermanualswhich,cumbersomeorjumbled,arebest
accommodatedinthelibraryandreadindoors.

WemayconcludethatthemajorpreoccupationsoftheMiddle
Englishhuntingmanualsarenotwiththepracticalproceduresof
thehunt,butwiththedetailsofterminologycorrecthunting
calls,andcategorisationofanimalswhichareoflittle
practicaluse.Thesepreoccupationsrevealtheattitudeofthe
authorstowardsthehunt-thatitwasessentiallyanoble,non-
utilitarianactivityinwhichknowledgeofformanddemonstration
ofthatknowledgewereofparamountimportance,ofmore
importancethantheostensibleaimofkillinganimals.

Thestyleandstructureofthehuntingmanualsreinforcethe
impressiongivenbytheircontents.Insteadofpresentingthe
materialaslucidlyandplainlyaspossible,theyemploy
artificialstructuresofdramaticinterchangeornarrative
sequence,andspurious'literariness'whichsometimesornament-
butsometimesobscure-thefactswhichitistheirfunctionto
communicate.

However,itwouldnotbefairtosuggestthatthehuntingmanuals
neglectcompletelythepracticaldetailsofthehunt.The
refinementswhichformthebasisoftheconcernwithterminology,
classification,huntingcallsandhornsignalsarenotpurely
cosmetic.Theyserveapracticalpurposeoftheirowninordering
theprocessofthehunt,infacilitatingcommunicationbetween
hunters,andincrystallisingthestructureofanactivitywhich
couldotherwisebechaotic.However,thesedetailshavebecomeso
refinedastoappearunrelatedtotherealbusinessofhunting,
